{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WYhoFiySNDK9621T341kio","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a solid understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### 1. Add `Exec` to ContainerRuntime interface\nNeed a way to run a command inside an existing container (docker exec). This is needed for container workflow resume.\n\n### 2. Add `ResumeRun` RPC to the gRPC service\n- New proto message: `ResumeRunRequest` with `run_id`, `step_name` (optional)\n- New proto message: `ResumeRunResponse` with `run_id`\n- New RPC: `ResumeRun`\n\n\n### 3. Implement `ResumeRun` on the server\n- Validate the run is in failed state\n- For container workflows: verify container exists and is stopped\n- Find the resume step (first failed step, or the specified step)\n- For container workflows: start container, exec `cloche-agent --resume` inside it\n- For host workflows: re-run from the resume step\n\n### 4. Add `cloche resume` CLI command\n- Parse args: `cloche resume <run-id> [step-name]`\n- Call `ResumeRun` RPC\n\n### 5. Implement resume logic in the agent\nImplementing the agent-side resume logic...\n\nWhen resuming, I need to preserve previous output files and handle each step type differently. For prompts, I'll use the conversation resume flag with a retry prompt, while scripts just re-run as-is, and workflow steps start fresh.\n\nFor container workflows, I'm realizing the container's original CMD has already finished, so I can't just restart it. Instead, I need to start the stopped container and then use `docker exec` to run the agent with resume flags inside it, tracking output the same way as a normal run. docker start) to get it running again\n2. Then docker exec to run the agent resume command\n3. Track output from the exec\n\nActually, this is more complex. Let me think about this differently.\n\nLooking at how the container starts:\n- `docker create` creates the container with a CMD that runs `cloche-agent`\n- `docker start` starts it\n- The agent runs and exits\n- The container stops (but is kept for failed runs)\n\nFor resume:\n- The container is stopped\n- We need to `docker start -a` it? No, that would re-run the original CMD.\n- We need to `docker start` it (to restart) then `docker exec` a new command inside.\n\nWait, actually no. When a Docker container exits, `docker start` restarts the container's main process. That would re-run the original workflow from scratch, which is not what we want.\n\nInstead, I could start the container and immediately exec into it with resume flags, though that means the original CMD runs in the background. Or I could avoid restarting entirely and instead copy the workspace state to a fresh container, then run the agent with resume flags there. The simplest path is probably to just start the container and exec the resume command, accepting that the original process runs alongside it. I need to rethink this—using `docker commit` to create a new image is too heavyweight. The real constraint is that the container filesystem needs to stay intact for the workflow, not that we reuse the same process. So I should copy any updated files into the stopped container, then restart it with the resume command instead of the original workflow command.\n\nBut `docker start` just re-runs the original CMD, which won't work for resume. I'm realizing I need `docker exec` to run commands on a container, but that requires the container to be running—and I can't change the CMD on an existing container to avoid running the original workflow first.\n\nThe better approach is to create a fresh container from the same image with the resume command baked in as the CMD, copy over the workspace from the old container, and track this new container instead. The output extraction is already handled, so I just need to wire up the container creation and workspace copying logic. even more carefully, I think the right approach is:\n\n1. `docker start` the stopped container (this restarts the PID 1 process which is the sh -c wrapper)\n2. Kill the sh -c wrapper immediately \n3. Use `docker exec` to run our resume command\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me look at what other systems do...\n\nActually, the cleanest Docker-based approach:\n1. `docker commit <old-container>` → creates a new image with the old container's filesystem\n2. Start a new container from that committed image with the resume command\n3. Track the new container\n4. Clean up the committed image after\n\nBut this involves creating temporary images, which is messy.\n\nLet me go even simpler. The cleanest approach for Docker:\n\n1. Copy the workspace from the old stopped container to a temp directory on the host\n2. Start a new container, copying that workspace in\n3. Run the agent with resume mode\n\nSo I need to preserve the workspace state from the old container—the installed dependencies and any changes made—while updating the project files themselves. For `docker start`, it would just re-execute the original command, which isn't what we want. The real issue is that the original CMD is wrapped in a shell that does setup work, so I need a different strategy to actually resume execution properly. ...'\"`. This will start running the original workflow again.\n\nThis is a problem. Let me think about this differently.\n\nAlternative: Don't use the original container at all. Just ensure the container hasn't been cleaned up (so its filesystem is available for docker cp). Then:\n1. Create a new container from the same image\n2. Copy workspace from old container to new container\n3. Also copy updated project files (overrides, scripts) on top\n4. Run with resume command\n\nThis approach:\n- Preserves the workspace state (deps, build artifacts, etc.) from the old container\n- Allows updated scripts to be applied\n- Runs a fresh agent process with resume flags\n\nLet me implement it this way.\n\nActually wait, there's an even simpler approach: For resume, I need the old container available so I can extract its workspace state. I'll copy the workspace from the old container to the new one, then start the new container with the resume command and let it pick up where it left off. The existing launchAndTrack already handles copying the project files, so I just need to additionally transfer the workspace state from the previous run.\n\nLooking back at the requirements: the old container needs to stay around for container workflows, script steps should rerun fresh but with outputs from preceding steps available, prompt steps should resume the conversation with the -c flag, and workflow steps start fresh. For resume to work, I need the previous step outputs (stored in `/workspace/.cloche/output/`) and conversation history available, plus any updated scripts applied on top. scripts may need to be applied\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to add an `Exec` method to ContainerRuntime that lets me execute commands in a running container. But there's a problem with resuming stopped containers—I can't just restart them with a different command since the container's CMD is fixed.\n\nLet me reconsider. I could use `docker commit` to snapshot the stopped container's state into a temporary image, then launch a new container from that image with the resume command. This would preserve the workspace, dependencies, and history while giving me a clean process with the right entrypoint.\n\nActually, I just realized there's a much simpler approach that avoids all this complexity. Since `docker cp` works on stopped containers, I can write a resume signal file directly into the container, then restart it with `docker start`. The agent already runs as the CMD, so it just needs to check for that signal file and resume from there—no commits, no exec, just a clean restart with the right behavior.\n\nThe resume config would be a JSON file containing the step to resume from and the mode. The agent reads this at startup and skips ahead accordingly, using the existing tracking infrastructure and keeping stdout as the communication channel.\n\nNow I need to implement this in the engine. The `Run()` method needs to handle resuming by skipping to the specified step.\n\nFor the engine changes, I could add a `ResumeFrom` field and modify `launchStep` to check if a step is before the resume point—if so, it returns any previous successful result immediately. The resume step and everything after execute normally. I need to figure out how to track which steps succeeded so I can replay them without re-executing. Still writing the executor wrapper...\n\nFor the resume step itself, I need to handle it differently depending on whether it's a prompt step or something else—prompt steps get the `-c` flag to continue the conversation, while scripts and workflows just re-run normally. The prompt adapter will need to recognize when it's in resume mode and use \"retry\" as the prompt instead of assembling a new one. Now I'm thinking through which files need changes to wire this all together. I need to continue mapping out the remaining files for the resume functionality, then verify whether the protobuf files are auto-generated or manually maintained so I know how to handle the proto changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5041,"cache_read_input_tokens":94221,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5041},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"46588779-0c89-4fa7-bd14-27979381b9bd","uuid":"3c8fd144-d230-43b7-af7c-589a7d656332"}
